51. Switchport Modes
========================
- one of the configuration being manually configured in the switch





DTP - Dynamic Trunking Protocol
=================================
- Negotiation protocol created by Cisco for 2 switches to automatically establish  a trunk link


Types Switchport Links
1. Trunk Links - Sends out DTP packets 
	Ex. Router to SW, Sw to SW
2. Access Links - Does not sends DTP packets
	Ex. SW to PC, Server or Printer







General Categories of Switchport Mode:
1. Administrative Mode - configured mode of an interface, can be manually configured and a default configuration for switch int. 
This is indeed the mode set by the network administrator and determines how the switchport is configured. 

a. Dynamic Administrative Mode: Uses Dynamic Trunking Protocol (DTP) to negotiate the port mode dynamically.
	- Dynamic Desirable: Actively initiates negotiation to establish a trunk link. Ready to trunk, actively sending packets. Dynamic mode is the default mode for the administrative mode.
		Syntax: SW1(config)#int fa0/1
			SW1(config)#switchport mode dynamic desirable
			SW1(config)#exit

		* default dynamic setting is commonly used by CORE and DISTRIBUTION switches 
							     -------------------------------   

	- Dynamic Auto: Passively waits for the other side to initiate trunk negotiation, only waiting to receive DTP packets, not sending DTP packets.
		Syntax: SW1(config)#int fa0/5
			SW1(config)#switchport mode dynamic auto
			SW1(config)#exit

		* dynamic auto is commonly  used by the ACCESS Switches
							------

b. Trunk Administrative Mode: Configured to carry traffic for multiple VLANs.
c. Access Administrative Mode: Configured for a single VLAN, connecting end devices like PCs or printers.

	

2. Operational Mode - actual mode of switch interface. This reflects the actual mode in which the switchport is functioning at any given moment. It will be either:

a. Access Mode: If the port is operating within a single VLAN.
	- Access port - port connected to an access link
b. Trunk Mode: If the port is carrying traffic from multiple VLANs.
	- Trunk port - port connected to a trunk link
	


To verify switchport mode: #sh int <int name> switchport

Statically or Manually Configured Switchport Modes
1. Static Trunk - unconditionally set to be trunk interface, sends out DTP packets
	Syntax: SW1(config)#int fa0/1
		SW1(config)#switchport mode trunk
		SW1(config)#exit
			
2. Static Access - unconditionally sets that interface to be an Access port, does not send DTP packets.
	Syntax: SW1(config)#int fa0/5
		SW1(config)#switchport mode access
		SW1(config)#exit

````
DTP Mode Negotiation Table
Administrative Mode	Operational Mode	Resulting Link State
Desirable	Desirable	Trunk
Desirable	Auto	Trunk
Auto	Auto	Access
Trunk	Trunk	Trunk
Access	Access	Down
Trunk	Access	Access
Nonegotiate	Nonegotiate	Disabled DTP negotiation
